==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wed
<hw>Wed</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>wedd</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>wed</ets>, OD. <ets>wedde</ets>,
OHG, <ets>wetti</ets>, G. <ets>wette</ets> a wager, Icel.
<ets>ve⟦edh⟧</ets> a pledge, Sw. <ets>vad</ets> a wager, an appeal,
Goth. <ets>wadi</ets> a pledge, Lith. <ets>vad⟦uring⟧ti</ets> to redeem
(a pledge), LL. <ets>vadium</ets>, L. <ets>vas</ets>, <ets>vadis</ets>,
bail, security, <ets>vadimonium</ets> security, and Gr. <?/, <?/ a
prize. Cf. <er>Athlete</er>, <er>Gage</er> a pledge,
<er>Wage</er>.]</ety> <def>A pledge; a pawn.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Gower. Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let him be ware, his neck lieth to <qex>wed</qex> [<it>i. e.</it>,
for a security].</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wed
<hw>Wed</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Wedded</conjf>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Wedded</conjf> or
<conjf>Wed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wedding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wedden</ets>, AS.
<ets>weddian</ets> to covenant, promise, to wed, marry; akin to OFries.
<ets>weddia</ets> to promise, D. <ets>wedden</ets> to wager, to bet, G.
<ets>wetten</ets>, Icel. <ets>ve⟦edh⟧ja</ets>, Dan. <ets>vedde</ets>,
Sw. <ets>v⟦aum⟧dja</ets> to appeal, Goth. ga<ets>wadj⟦omac⟧n</ets> to
betroth. See <er>Wed</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To take for husband or for wife by a formal
ceremony; to marry; to espouse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With this ring I thee <qex>wed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bk. of Com.
Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I saw thee first, and <qex>wedded</qex> thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To join in marriage; to give in wedlock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Adam, <qex>wedded</qex> to another Eve,⟦br⟧
Shall live with her.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fig.: To unite as if by the affections or the bond
of marriage; to attach firmly or indissolubly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou art <qex>wedded</qex> to calamity.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men are <qex>wedded</qex> to their lusts.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Flowers] are <qex>wedded</qex> thus, like beauty to old age.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To take to one's self and support; to espouse.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They positively and concernedly <qex>wedded</qex> his cause.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wed
<hw>Wed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To contact matrimony;
to marry.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧When I shall <xex>wed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weddahs</ent>⟦br⟧
